Let’s find the inverse function of $f(x)$.  The inverse function, denoted by $f^{-1}(x)$, will ‘un-do’ the function $f(x)$.  Let $y=f(x)=\dfrac{2}{x+1}$ and solve for $x$:
\begin{align*}
y&=\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\
y(x+1)&=2 \\
yx+y&=2 \\
yx&=2-y \\
x&=\dfrac{2-y}{y} \\
f^{-1}(y)&=\dfrac{2-y}{y}
\end{align*}Now, we can find the value of $f^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)$:
\begin{align*}
f^{-1}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)&=\dfrac{2-\frac{1}{5}}{\frac{1}{5}} \\
&= \dfrac{\frac{9}{5}}{\frac{1}{5}} \\
&= \boxed{9}
\end{align*}
